        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/74df32/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-12-29T08:38:10.146Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Avitus\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"73878\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/48/34172_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Avitus:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you have enough people in a Signal group, the security value of it is no longer relevant</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Not true. The attacker still need to make an effort to join the group, compared to plaintext communication subject to mass surveillance.</p>\n<p>Just like the example you‚Äôve linked, the encryption in big groups forces attackers to spent time and resources on chosen target, instead of gathering everything ‚Äújust because we can‚Äù. While it won‚Äôt be any consolation for members of the group with snitch in it, this is big security value gain overall.</p>",
